---
description: Prefer positive conditions; allow negative early exits
alwaysApply: true
---

# Condition Reading Flow

- Prefer positive conditions in main control flow to keep code easy to read left-to-right.
- Avoid negative conditions (`!foo`, `!==`, `if (!x) { ... }` as the main branch) unless the branch is an early return or error throw.
- Negative null/undefined checks are also allowed (for example `if (!value)`, `if (value == null)`, `if (value === null)`), especially as guards.
- Negative guard clauses are encouraged when they exit quickly (e.g. `return`, `continue`, `break`, `throw`) and keep the main path unindented.
- For non-early branches, prefer rewriting to positive form.

Examples:

```ts
// Preferred (negative condition used only as an early return)
if (!shouldAttemptRefresh(request, response.status)) {
  return response;
}
await refreshAndRetry(request);

// Avoid (negative condition as main branch)
if (!isReady) {
  process();
} else {
  skip();
}
```
